    <weatherForecast/>
    <avalancheActivity>
      <highlights>Slight increase in danger of moist and wet avalanches as a consequence of warming during the day. Individual gliding avalanches can also occur.</highlights>
      <comment>The surface of the snowpack is frozen, but not to a significant depth and will soften earlier than the day before. The weather conditions will cause a slight rise in the danger of moist avalanches as the day progresses in particular at intermediate altitudes. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> In particular above approximately 2200 m: Weak layers in the old snowpack can still be released in some place by winter sport participants, after an overcast night in particular.</comment>
    </avalancheActivity>
    <snowpackStructure>
      <comment>In particular in the vicinity of peaks snow depths vary greatly, depending on the infuence of the wind. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> Intermediate and high altitudes: Weak layers exist in the snowpack especially on west, north and northeast facing slopes. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> In the vicinity of peaks snow depths vary greatly, depending on the infuence of the wind. In places that are protected from the wind in all altitude zones a lot of snow is lying for the time of year.</comment>
    </snowpackStructure>
    <travelAdvisory/>
    <tendency>
      <tendencyType>steady</tendencyType>
